definition.value: A polyhedral polysilsesquioxane.
A polyhedral oligomeric silsesquioxane containing fluorinated R groups.
A macromolecule with a [-Si(R2)-O-] repeating unit.
An  acetylenic and an olefinic  compound containing a carbon chain that contains a carbon-carbon double bond and a carbon-carbon triple bond.
An acetylenic compound containing three carbon-carbon triple bonds.
A triyne amide produced by the Brazilian fungus Agrocybe perfecta (Basidiomycota).
Any acetylenic compound containing four carbon-carbon triple bonds.
The conjugate base of any hydroxy fatty acid, formed by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid moiety.
A fatty acid anion carrying one or more oxo substituents

The hydrochloride salt of doxapram. A central and respiratory stimulant with a brief duration of action, both doxapram hydrochloride and its hydrate are used as a temporary treatment of acute respiratory failure, particularly when superimposed on chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, and of postoperative respiratory depression. It has also been used for treatment of postoperative shivering.
Compounds with the structure R2NC(=O)C(=O)H.
The simplest of the class of glyoxamides, with no substitution on nitrogen.
A compound containing a single glyoxamide unit.
A compound containing two glyoxamide units.
The (R)-enantiomer of doxapram.
The (S)-enantiomer of doxapram.
A drug used for the treatment of hyperplasia (increaced cell production within an organ or tissue).

Any fatty acid with a hydroxy functional group in the beta- or 3-position. beta-Hydroxy fatty acids accumulate during cardiac hypoxia, and can also be used as chemical markers of bacterial endotoxins.
The (R)-enantiomer of dyphylline.
The (S)-enantiomer of dyphylline.
The conjugate base of any thia fatty acid, formed by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid moiety.

The iodide salt of ecothiopate. An irreversible acetylcholinesterase inhibitor, it is used an ocular antihypertensive in the treatment of open-angle glaucoma, particularly when other drugs have proved inadequate.

A polysaccharide derivative composed of a backbone of linear trisaccharide-derivative repeating units that are joined to each other via alpha-(1->3)-linkages. An antigen, it is the O-polysaccharide of the lipopolysaccharide from Acinetobacter haemolyticus strain 57.
Any compound containing a (halomethyl)benzene skeleton.
Any benzyl halide containing a (chloromethyl)benzene skeleton.

A polysaccharide derivative composed of a backbone of linear trisaccharide-derivative repeating units that are joined to each other via beta-(1->3)-linkages. An antigen, it is the O-polysaccharide of the lipopolysaccharide from Acinetobacter haemolyticus strain 61.

An O-polysaccharide composed of a backbone of linear trisaccharide repeating units that are joined to each other via beta-(1->4)-linkages. An antigen, it is the O-specific side chain of Pseudomonas aeruginosa immunotype 3 lipopolysaccharide.
Compounds containing a (bromomethyl)benzene skeleton.
A member of the class of benzyl bromides that is toluene substituted on the alpha-carbon with bromine.
A compound of formula PhCH2OR (R =/= H).
The 3-O-benzyl and 6-myristyl derivative of morphine, for which it is a prodrug. Myrophine is almost invariably used as the hydrochloride.

An amino tetrasaccharide and epitope consisting of L-glycero-alpha-D-manno-heptopyranose having a lactosyl moiety attached at the 3-position via an alpha-linkage and an alpha-N-acetylglucosaminyl residue at the 2-position.
The hydrochloride salt of myrophine.
The conjugate base of D-fructofuranuronic acid.
Any drug used to depigment skin, normally by decreasing the excretion of melanin from melanocytes.

The fumaric acid salt of emedastine containing two molecules of fumaric acid for each molecule of emedastine. A relatively selective histamine H1 antagonist, it is used for allergic rhinitis, urticaria, and pruritic skin disorders, and in eyedrops for the symptomatic relief of allergic conjuntivitis.

label.value: P. aeruginosa serotype O11 O-specific polysaccharide

definition.value: A polysaccharide composed of a backbone of linear trisaccharide repeating units that are joined to each other via beta-(1->4)-linkages. An epitope, it is the O-polysaccharide portion of the lipopolysaccharide from Pseudomonas aeruginosa serotype O11.
A glycosylmannose consisting of alpha-D-mannopyranose having an alpha-abequopyranosyl residue attached at the 3-position.
A branched octasaccharide consisting of two repeating tetrasaccharide units; isolated from phage P22 endo-rhamnosidase cleaved S. typhimurium O-polysaccharide chains.
Zwitterionic form of an L-alpha-amino acid having an anionic carboxy group and a protonated amino group.
A quassinoid consisting of a heteropentacyclic skeleton containing a delta-lactone moiety which is substituted at the alpha-carbon by a 3-methylbutanoyloxy group.
Polyketide compounds that are synthesized from six ketide units. They are derivatives of a 12-carbon skeleton.
Zwitterionic form of a D-alpha-amino acid having an anionic carboxy group and a protonated amino group.
Polyketide compounds that are synthesized from seven ketide units. They are derivatives of a 14-carbon skeleton.
A hexaketide lactone isolated from the sponge-associated fungus Cladosporium sp. It is a diastereoisomer of pandangolide 1a.
A carboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of an N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid arising from deprotonation of the C-1 carboxy group.
A hexaketide lactone isolated from the sponge-associated fungus Cladosporium sp. It is a diastereoisomer of pandangolide 1.
